            <section class="article-section">
                <h2 class="section-title"><i class="fas fa-chart-bar"></i> The Combatants: 7 Stocks vs 500 Stocks</h2>
                <h3 class="subsection-title">Bro Billionaire Stocks (7 names)</h3>
                <p><strong>The Lineup:</strong> Nvidia, Tesla, Microsoft, Apple, Amazon, Meta, Palantir<br>
                    <strong>Combined Market Cap:</strong> $14 trillion<br> <strong>Strategy:</strong> Concentrated
                    conviction in disruptive tech leaders<br> <strong>5-Year Return:</strong> +850% average</p>
                <h3 class="subsection-title">S&P 500 Index (500 names)</h3>
                <p><strong>The Lineup:</strong> 500 largest US publicly traded companies<br> <strong>Combined Market
                        Cap:</strong> $45 trillion<br> <strong>Strategy:</strong> Diversified market-cap weighted US
                    equities<br> <strong>5-Year Return:</strong> +95%</p>
                <p><strong>The Twist:</strong> The S&P 500's top 7 holdings ARE the Bro Billionaire Stocks (minus
                    Palantir). They comprise 30%+ of the index. So when you buy SPY, you're getting diluted exposure to
                    the same winners plus 493 other companies.</p>
